[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-arkansas-territory-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election] The **1828 Arkansas Territory at-large congressional district special election** was held on December 15, 1828, following the death of Henry W.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-arkansas-territory-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election] Conway, who had served as the Democratic-Republican Party delegate to Congress from Arkansas Territory since 1823.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-arkansas-territory-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election] The position was for the territory's lone non-voting delegate to the United States House of Representatives.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-arkansas-territory-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election] Delegate Henry Conway died from a wound sustained in a duel with Robert Crittenden on October 29, 1827.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-arkansas-territory-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election] Following Conway's death, Governor of Arkansas Territory George Izard issued a proclamation calling for a special election on the third Monday in December 1828.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-arkansas-territory-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election] Five candidates announced for the position, with two later withdrawing.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-connecticut-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] The **1828 Connecticut lieutenant gubernatorial election** was held on April 10, 1828, in order to elect the lieutenant governor of Connecticut.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-connecticut-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] Incumbent National Republican lieutenant governor John Samuel Peters won re-election as he ran with minimal opposition.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-connecticut-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] On election day, April 10, 1828, incumbent National Republican lieutenant governor John Samuel Peters won re-election with 92.60% of the vote, thereby retaining National Republican control over the office of lieutenant governor.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-connecticut-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] Peters was sworn in for his second term on May 7, 1828.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] The **1828 Indiana gubernatorial election** took place on August 4, 1828, under the provisions of the Constitution of Indiana.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] It was the fifth gubernatorial election in the State of Indiana.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Ray, the incumbent governor, was re-elected, defeating Israel T.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Canby, the former state senator representing Jefferson and Jennings counties, and Harbin H.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Moore, the outgoing speaker of the Indiana House of Representatives, in a three-way race.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] The election took place concurrently with races for lieutenant governor and members of the Indiana General Assembly.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Ray won the 1825 Indiana gubernatorial election after succeeding to the governorship upon the resignation of William Hendricks, who had stepped down to accept a seat in the United States Senate.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] From the beginning, his tenure was controversial: opponents alleged Ray was yet shy of the minimum age of thirty years when he took the oath of office, and his ascension as such had been unconstitutional.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] (In fact, Ray turned thirty a few days after his inauguration, but continued to serve as governor regardless.) Following his re-election to a full term in August 1825, Ray attempted to steer a middle course between the emerging Jacksonian and Anti-Jacksonian factions in federal politics.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] His independent stance attracted criticisms from both camps, as did his acceptance of a federal commission in 1826 to negotiate the Treaty of Mississinewas, which appeared to violate the constitutional prohibition against governors serving in federal employ during their tenure in office.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] The General Assembly debated whether Ray had forfeited his office by accepting the commission, and separately, whether he had neglected his duties by absenting himself from the capital for long periods.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Indiana State Treasurer Samuel Merrill attacked Ray publicly, alleging the governor to be "destitute of principle and all sense of propriety," and accusing him of embezzling public funds.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Ultimately, an investigative committee found no evidence of wrongdoing, and a resolution calling for Ray's removal was defeated in the House by a vote of 31 to 27.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] For the first time, presidential politics played a significant role in the gubernatorial election.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] The 1828 United States presidential election pitted President John Quincy Adams against challenger Andrew Jackson four years after Adams narrowly bested Jackson in a hard-fought campaign that had to be decided by the U.S.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Opposition to Ray's re-election abounded as the 1828 election came into view.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] The dispute with Merrill, while acrimonious, remained personal in nature, and failed to mobilize the public against him.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Far more damaging was Ray's studied neutrality in the brewing rematch between Adams and Jackson.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] For the first time since 1816, (when Indiana's electoral votes were awarded by the state legislature,) the presidential and gubernatorial contests would occur in the same year.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Supporters of Adams and Jackson held their presidential preference in mind as they considered the candidates for governor.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Attempting to appeal to both factions, Ray pleased neither.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] His position attracted rivals from across the political spectrum, and Ray had to endure attacks from both Jacksonians and Anti-Jacksonians throughout the campaign.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Ray feared a challenger backed by supporters of President Adams would split the electorate along partisan lines.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] In 1824 he had supported Henry Clay for president but preferred Jackson over Adams in the ensuing contingent election in the House of Representatives.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] While the 1825 gubernatorial election had not been fought along partisan lines, Ray's opponent in that contest, Chief Justice Isaac Blackford, was a known "Adams man." Blackford, Lieutenant Governor John H.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Thompson, and Speaker Moore were each proposed as potential candidates for governor in the winter of 1827–28.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] All three were known to favor Adams in the approaching presidential election; Moore had actually been a delegate to the Adams State Convention in January 1828 that nominated a slate of electors pledged to Adams and adopted a platform defending the policies of the administration.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Thompson was the leading candidate against Ray until early April, when Moore's candidacy began to pick up steam.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] No candidate was ever formally endorsed as the "Adams" or "National Republican" nominee for governor, though Moore's presidential preference was known publicly and remarked on in the strategic considerations of the rival Jacksonians.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Israel Canby emerged as the early favorite among Jacksonians in 1828; a physician and member of the state senate from Madison, he had been a delegate to the Jackson State Conventions of 1824 and 1828.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] When the 1828 convention adjourned, some Jacksonians went away with the understanding that Canby had been nominated for governor.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Canby, however, had determined to withdraw his candidacy for personal considerations.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] In early May, as it became apparent Ray would be opposed in the gubernatorial election by an Adams man, the Jackson State Committee saw fit to approach the governor with the offer of an endorsement.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Ray wrote in reply that the committee could "dispose of me and my name as you in your wisdom see fit," that he would not commit himself to either candidate for president but would nonetheless welcome "the united support of the Jacksonians" in the August election.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] He asked only that Jacksonian support, were it forthcoming, remain private until after the election to avoid any appearance of partisanship.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Subsequent events would cause Canby to re-enter the race in early July with less than a month left in the campaign.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Twelve years after statehood, Indiana was still a frontier state, and enthusiasm for internal improvements was unanimous and bipartisan.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] The Jacksonians sought to make an issue of the upcoming presidential election, which due to the staggered electoral calendar would be held in November, two months after the gubernatorial contest.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Despite intense pressure to declare a preference, Ray remained steadfastly neutral in the presidential contest, decrying the spirit of partisanship endemic in state politics.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Campaigning was conducted, not only by sympathetic editors in the press, but by the candidates themselves.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Ray conducted a tour of ten counties in the company of U.S.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Blake, addressing crowds in Brookville, Lawrenceburg and Vincennes.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Ray's incumbency was an asset to his campaign, as he was better known to the public than either Canby or Moore, who could not rival the governor's long-established reputation.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] In June the pro-Adams editor of the Brookville *Repository*, Augustus Jocelyn, published an interview with Ray that dealt a severe blow to the governor's budding alliance with the Jacksonians.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Jocelyn quoted Ray as denying the 1824 presidential election had been stolen from Jackson and denouncing the Jackson party as "an outrageous and violent faction" which it was "the duty of every good man" to oppose.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] In response, the Jackson State Committee cut all ties with Ray and published in full their previous correspondence, and Canby, his private business now concluded, re-emerged as a candidate for governor.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] His alliance with the Jackson party had been only prospective, in the event the Adams faction were to mount a partisan campaign against him; as for his description of Jacksonians as "outrageous and violent," Ray said, the remark was entirely Jocelyn's invention.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Ray defeated his two opponents less than 40% of the statewide vote, polling strongest in the counties of the Whitewater Valley.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Canby's support came mostly from southern counties that would go on to favor Jackson in the October presidential election, as well as Terre Haute, while Moore carried a total of nine counties along the periphery of the state.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] The relationship between presidential party identity and voter behavior in the gubernatorial election is ambiguous.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Carmony writes that while the election results show some degree of correlation between presidential preference and gubernatorial politics, "local and personal preferences remained strong." Ray carried thirty-two counties, winning votes from both Jacksonians and Anti-Jacksonians in equal numbers.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Despite this, he became the first governor to be elected with less than a majority of the votes.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-kentucky-gubernatorial-election] The **1828 Kentucky gubernatorial election** was held on August 4, 1828.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-kentucky-gubernatorial-election] Incumbent Democratic-Republican Governor Joseph Desha was term-limited, and could not seek a second consecutive term.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-kentucky-gubernatorial-election] National Republican nominee Thomas Metcalfe defeated Democratic nominee William T.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-kentucky-s-2nd-congressional-district-special-election] A **special election** was held in **Kentucky's 2nd congressional district** on August 4, **1828** to fill a vacancy in Kentucky's representation.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-kentucky-s-2nd-congressional-district-special-election] In the 1827 elections, Thomas Metcalfe (A) was re-elected to a 5th term and served until June 1, 1828 when he resigned to run for governor.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election] The **1828 Louisiana gubernatorial election** was the fifth gubernatorial election to take place after Louisiana achieved statehood.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election] Under Article III Sec 2 of the 1812 Constitution of the State of Louisiana the Governor was elected in two steps.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election] On the first Monday in July, eligible voters went to the polls and voted.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election] The returns were sent to the President of the Louisiana State Senate.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election] On the second day of the session of the Louisiana State Legislature, the Louisiana House of Representatives and Senate met in joint session and voted between the top two candidates.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-louisiana-gubernatorial-election] The candidate who received a majority in General Assembly became governor.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election] The **1828 Massachusetts gubernatorial election** was held on April 7.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election] Governor Levi Lincoln Jr., an Adams supporter, was re-elected to a fourth term in office over Democrat Marcus Morton, of the Jacksonian faction.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election] Morton carried only eighteen towns, all of them rural with the exception of Charlestown.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-massachusetts-gubernatorial-election] The others were Adams, Cheshire, New Ashford, Alford, Tyringham, Montgomery, Westfield, Southwick, Holland, Dana, Charlton, Oxford, Sutton, Seekonk, Berkley, Freetown, and Woburn.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] Elections to the United States House of Representatives were held in Pennsylvania on October 14, 1828, for the 21st Congress.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] Members of three different parties were elected to the 21st Congress, the first time in US history that a third party won seats.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] The new Anti-Masonic Party won a total of 5 seats, 1 of which was in Pennsylvania.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] In the previous election, 20 Jacksonians and 5 Anti-Jacksonians had been elected with one vacancy, which was filled in a special election by an Anti-Jacksonian, for a total of 20 Jacksonians and 6 Anti-Jacksonians.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] 20 incumbents (15 Jacksonians and 5 Anti-Jacksonians) ran for re-election, of whom 12 (all Jacksonians) were re-elected.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] The incumbents Charles Miner (AJ) of the 4th district, George Kremer (J), Espy Van Horne (J), and Samuel McKean (J) of the 9th district, John Mitchell (J) of the 12th district and Robert Orr, Jr.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] (J) of the 16th district did not run for re-election.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] One seat changed from Jacksonian control to Anti-Masonic control, one changed from Jacksonian to Anti-Jacksonian, and six changed from Anti-Jacksonian to Jacksonian, for a net change of five seats lost by the Anti-Jacksonians, four gained by the Jacksonians, and one gained by the Anti-Masonics.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] Two special elections were held in 1829 for the 21st Congress.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] The first was held on October 13, 1829 in the 8th district to fill two vacancies caused by the resignations of Samuel D.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] Ingham (J) and George Wolf (J) before the first meeting of the 21st Congress.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] Wolf's resignation was due to his having been elected Governor of Pennsylvania.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] The second was held on December 15, 1829 in the 16th district, to fill a vacancy caused by the resignation of William Wilkins (AM) on November 9, 1829, before the first session of the 21st Congress began.
[src:1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania/1828-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-pennsylvania] No seat changed parties after these special elections.
